library(tidyverse)
library(albersusa)
library(readr)
library(data.table)

HAF_joined <- read_csv("HAF_joined.csv")
api_acs_join_ready <- read_csv("api_acs_join_ready.csv")
api_med_month_inc <- read_csv("api_med_month_inc.csv")

Joining

HAF_ACS_join <- HAF_joined %>%
  left_join(api_acs_join_ready, by = c("fips"="full_fips"))

HAF_ACS_join <- HAF_ACS_join %>%
  left_join(api_med_month_inc, by = c("fips"="full_fips"))

HAF_ACS_full <- HAF_ACS_join %>%
  mutate(api_total_med_owner_cost = replace(api_total_med_owner_cost, 
                                            api_total_med_owner_cost == -666666666, NA),
         api_cost_to_income_ratio = api_total_med_owner_cost/api_month_med_income)

Condense

HAF_ACS_analyze <- HAF_ACS_full %>%
  select(c(1,4,6,7,13,14,17,19,
           30,35,
           38:51,
           53,54))

# fwrite(HAF_ACS_analyze, "~\\HAF_ACS_analyze.csv")

Visualizations

# Map of county boundaries in US, these give you the data to put stuff on the map
us_county <- counties_sf("laea") #load in county outline
## old-style crs object detected; please recreate object with a recent sf::st_crs()
outline_states <- usa_sf("laea") #load in state outline
## old-style crs object detected; please recreate object with a recent sf::st_crs()
# This function creates the base of the map
my_map_theme <- function(){
  theme(panel.background=element_blank(),
        axis.text=element_blank(),
        axis.ticks=element_blank(),
        axis.title=element_blank())
}

# This is an example of a blank map
# Get base form visualization
ggplot(us_county) + 
  geom_sf(size=0.25) + #sets county lines
  geom_sf(data = outline_states, alpha=0, size=0.5, color="black") + #thickens state lines
  my_map_theme() +
  labs(title = "This is a title",
       subtitle = "This is a subtitle") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size=15)) +
  theme(plot.subtitle = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

# Joining with the geometry to get the map data & cutting out the data that is not available from our original data (Shannon County, South Dakota; Bedford City, Virginia; Wade Hampton Census Area, Alaska)
HAF_ACS_viz <- us_county %>%
  filter(fips != "46113", 
         fips != "02270",
         fips != "51515") %>%
  left_join(HAF_ACS_analyze, by=c("fips"="fips"))
# Making a discrete scale
# You need cut off points, labels for them, and discrete colors on a scale

# I'm doing this for cost-to-income ratio based on the ACS data pulled from the Census API

# Look at the range of the variable you're working with to base your cutpoints and labels on

range(HAF_ACS_viz$api_cost_to_income_ratio, na.rm = T)
## [1] 0.08456252 0.96655480
ratio_cutpoints <- c(-0.001, 0.050, 0.100, 
                     0.200, 0.225, 0.250, 0.275,
                     0.300, 0.400, 0.500, 0.600, 0.700, 1.000)

ratio_labels <- c("0.00% to 5.00%", "5.00% to 10.0%", "10.0% to 20.0%", 
                  "20.0% to 22.5%", "22.5% to 25.0%", "25.0% to 27.5%", "27.5% to 30.0%", 
                  "30.0% to 40.0%", "40.0% to 50.0%", "50.0% to 60.0%", "60.0% to 70.0%",
                  "70.0% or more")

ratio_colors <- c("#fff0a6", "#ffe871", "#ffdc39",
                  "#ffb34e", "#e4a06a", "#de8565", "#de7565",
                  "#de6565", "#be5151", "#9e3636", "#6f1e1e",
                  "#390808")

# Adding in the discrete categories into the data
ratio_viz <- HAF_ACS_viz %>%
  mutate(ratio_interval = cut(api_cost_to_income_ratio, 
                              breaks = ratio_cutpoints, 
                              labels = ratio_labels))

p <- ggplot(ratio_viz) + 
  geom_sf(aes(fill=ratio_interval), size=0.25, color="#2d2d2d") + #sets county lines
  scale_fill_manual("Cost-to-Income Ratio", values = ratio_colors) +
  geom_sf(data = outline_states, alpha=0, size=0.5, color="black") + #thickens state lines
  my_map_theme() +
  labs(title = "Median Monthly Cost-to-Income Ratio by County in 2019",
       subtitle = "Looking at the Proportion of Homeowner Costs and Income for All Homeowners",
       caption = "*Bedford City, VA; Shannon County, SD; & Wade Census Area, AK are whited out due to not being included in Urban's data") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size=15)) +
  theme(plot.subtitle = element_text(hjust = 0.5)) +
